# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1777-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The **1777 Delaware gubernatorial election** was held on February 12, 1777.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1777-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The president of the committee of safety John McKinly was elected president of Delaware for a term of three years.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1777-delaware-gubernatorial-election] McKinly, a physician and a militia officer from Wilmington, Delaware, was a political moderate chosen for his ability to appeal to all factions in the revolutionary government.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1777-delaware-gubernatorial-election] His lack of distinction led critics to dismiss the incoming president as "a mere patch upon the back" of the powerful president of the Council George Read.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1777-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Delaware General Assembly.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1777-delaware-gubernatorial-election] McKinly was elected with a majority on the first ballot.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1778-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The **1778 Delaware gubernatorial election** was held on March 31, 1778.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1778-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The delegate to the Continental Congress from Delaware Caesar Rodney was elected president of Delaware for a term of three years.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1778-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The previous president John McKinly was captured by the British Army in September 1777, less than a year into his three-year term.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1778-delaware-gubernatorial-election] In succession, the speaker of the Assembly Thomas McKean and the president of the Council George Read acted as president pending the election of McKinly's successor.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1778-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Rodney was elected with a majority on the first ballot.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1781-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The **1781 Delaware gubernatorial election** was held on November 6, 1781.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1781-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The councilor from Kent County John Dickinson was elected president of Delaware for a term of three-years.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1781-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Delaware politics during the 1780s witnessed the rise of conservative and radical political factions, with the radical leaders predominating during the American War of Independence.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1781-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The withdraw of British Army forces from Philadelphia in 1779 preceded the rise of the conservative faction, with which Dickinson, formerly an opponent of American independence, was associated.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1781-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Dickinson's election to succeed the radical outgoing president Caesar Rodney represented the ascendency of a nationalist group of Founding Fathers who favored a more powerful central government for the United States.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1781-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Dickinson was elected with a majority on the first ballot.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The **1783 Delaware gubernatorial election** was held on February 1, 1783.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The former delegate to the Congress of the Confederation from Delaware Nicholas Van Dyke was elected president of Delaware for a term of three years.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The previous president John Dickinson resigned on November 4, 1782, following his election as president of Pennsylvania.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The president of the Council John Cook acted as president pending the election of Dickinson's successor.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Delaware politics during the 1780s witnessed the rise of conservative and radical political factions, with Dickinson's 1781 election reflecting the early-decade conservative ascendancy.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Dickinson's resignation represented a victory for the radicals, who led the public backlash against nonresident officeholding.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Following Dickinson's ouster, conservative leaders were thought to favor the former president John McKinly or the chief justice of the Delaware Supreme Court William Killen to succeed Cook, but radical opposition in the legislature defeated their candidacies.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Van Dyke's election was interpreted as a rebuke of Pennsylvanian influence over the state government.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1783-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Van Dyke was elected with a majority on the first ballot.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1786-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The **1786 Delaware gubernatorial election** was held on October 27, 1786.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1786-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The judge of the Delaware Court of Common Pleas Thomas Collins was elected president of Delaware for a term of three years.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1786-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The conservative political faction in Delaware politics had regained the ascendancy following their defeat in the last election, and in 1786 took control of the Delaware House of Assembly.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1786-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Collins, a militia officer and respected landowner from Kent County, Delaware, was considered broadly acceptable to all factions.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1786-delaware-gubernatorial-election] Collins was elected unanimously on the first ballot.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1786-delaware-gubernatorial-election] The number of votes cast was not recorded.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-delaware] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] The **1828 United States presidential election in Delaware** took place between October 31 and December 2, 1828, as part of the 1828 United States presidential election.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] Voters chose three representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] Delaware cast three electoral votes for the National Republican candidate, John Quincy Adams, over the Democratic candidate, Andrew Jackson.
[src:1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware/1828-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] These electors were elected by the Delaware General Assembly, the state legislature, rather than by popular vote.
